Project: Model Tuning - ReneWind¶

Business Context¶

Renewable energy sources play an increasingly important role in the global energy mix, as the effort to reduce the environmental impact of energy production increases.

Out of all the renewable energy alternatives, wind energy is one of the most developed technologies worldwide. The U.S Department of Energy has put together a guide to achieving operational efficiency using predictive maintenance practices.

Predictive maintenance uses sensor information and analysis methods to measure and predict degradation and future component capability. The idea behind predictive maintenance is that failure patterns are predictable and if component failure can be predicted accurately and the component is replaced before it fails, the costs of operation and maintenance will be much lower.

The sensors fitted across different machines involved in the process of energy generation collect data related to various environmental factors (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) and additional features related to various parts of the wind turbine (gearbox, tower, blades, break, etc.).

Objective¶

“ReneWind” is a company working on improving the machinery/processes involved in the production of wind energy using machine learning and has collected data of generator failure of wind turbines using sensors. They have shared a ciphered version of the data, as the data collected through sensors is confidential (the type of data collected varies with companies). Data has 40 predictors, 20000 observations in the training set and 5000 in the test set.

The objective is to build various classification models, tune them, and find the best one that will help identify failures so that the generators could be repaired before failing/breaking to reduce the overall maintenance cost. The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model. These will result in repairing costs.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures where there is no detection by the model. These will result in replacement costs.
  • False positives (FP) are detections where there is no failure. These will result in inspection costs.

It is given that the cost of repairing a generator is much less than the cost of replacing it, and the cost of inspection is less than the cost of repair.

“1” in the target variables should be considered as “failure” and “0” represents “No failure”.

Data Description¶

  • The data provided is a transformed version of original data which was collected using sensors.
  • Train.csv - To be used for training and tuning of models.
  • Test.csv - To be used only for testing the performance of the final best model.
  • Both the datasets consist of 40 predictor variables and 1 target variable

# Displays a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.
def histogram_boxplot_grid(data):
    """
    Grid of boxplots and histograms for each feature in the dataset.
    data: training dataset
    """

    features = data.columns[:-1]  # Exclude the target column

    ncols = 4
    nrows = len(features) // ncols + (len(features) % ncols > 0)  # Calculate number of rows needed

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows * 2, ncols=ncols, figsize=(20, 5 * nrows), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 3] * nrows})

    for i, feature in enumerate(features):
        row, col = divmod(i, ncols)
        ax_box = axes[row * 2, col]
        ax_hist = axes[row * 2 + 1, col]

        # Plot the boxplot and histogram
        sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, palette="coolwarm")
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist, palette="winter")

        # Add mean and median lines to the histogram
        ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")
        ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")

        # Hide the x-axis labels for the boxplot
        ax_box.set_xlabel('')
        ax_box.set_xticks([])

    # Adjust the layout and remove empty subplots
    plt.tight_layout()
    for ax in axes.flat:
        if not ax.get_children():  # Check if the subplot is empty
            fig.delaxes(ax)  # Remove the empty subplot

# Displays Missing Values as a Dataframe
def missing_values_table(dataframe):
    """
    Display features with missing values, their count, and percentage of missing values.

    dataframe: pandas DataFrame
    """
    # Calculate the missing values for each feature
    missing_values = dataframe.isnull().sum()

    # Filter out features with no missing values
    missing_values = missing_values[missing_values > 0]

    # Calculate the percentage of missing values
    missing_percentage = (missing_values / len(dataframe)) * 100

    # Create a table with the results
    missing_table = pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature Name': missing_values.index,
        'Missing Value Count': missing_values.values,
        'Missing Value Percentage': missing_percentage.values
    })

    # Sort the table by the percentage of missing values in descending order
    missing_table = missing_table.sort_values(by='Missing Value Percentage', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

    # Display the table
    if not missing_table.empty:
        return missing_table
    else:
        return "No missing values found in the dataset."

# Displays a heatmap of significant correlation between features.
def significant_correlations(dataframe, annot=True, threshold=0.5):
    """
    dataframe: pandas DataFrame
    annot: display correlation value True or False
    threshold: minimum absolute value of correlation coefficient to be considered significant (default 0.5)
    """
    # Exclude the target variable
    features = dataframe.drop(columns=['Target'])

    # Calculate the correlation matrix
    corr_matrix = features.corr()

    # Filter out correlations below the threshold and the diagonal (self-correlations)
    significant_corr = corr_matrix[abs(corr_matrix) >= threshold]
    significant_corr = significant_corr[significant_corr != 1]

    # Plot the heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))
    sns.heatmap(significant_corr, annot=annot, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', vmin=-1, vmax=1)
    plt.title('Significant Correlations between Features')
    plt.show()

# Prints a table for each variable with significantly high correlation with other variables.
def print_significant_correlations(dataframe, threshold=0.5):
    """
    dataframe: pandas DataFrame
    threshold: minimum absolute value of correlation coefficient to be considered significant (default 0.5)
    """
    # Exclude the target variable
    features = dataframe.drop(columns=['Target'])

    # Calculate the correlation matrix
    corr_matrix = features.corr()

    # Iterate through each variable and print the significant correlations
    for variable in corr_matrix.columns:
        significant_corrs = corr_matrix[(abs(corr_matrix[variable]) >= threshold) & (corr_matrix[variable] != 1)][variable]
        if not significant_corrs.empty:
            print(f"Variable '{variable}' has significant correlations with:")
            print(significant_corrs.to_string(), '\n')

# Plots bivariate analysis charts depicting relationship between features and target variable.
def plot_bivariate_analysis_tv(df, target_variable, figsize_per_chart=(5, 4)):
    """
    Parameters:
    - df: pandas DataFrame
    - target_variable: str, the name of the target variable column in the DataFrame
    - figsize_per_chart: tuple, optional, the size of each subplot
    """
    # Create feature list
    features = df.columns.tolist()
    features.remove(target_variable) # Exclude the target variable

    # Total number of features
    total_features = len(features)

    # Calculate total rows needed for subplots (4 charts per row)
    total_rows = ceil(total_features / 4)

    # Create a figure for subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(total_rows, 4, figsize=(figsize_per_chart[0]*4, figsize_per_chart[1]*total_rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()  # Flatten to 1D for easy indexing

    # Plot for numerical features
    for i, feature in enumerate(features):
        sns.boxplot(x=target_variable, y=feature, data=df, ax=axes[i], palette="coolwarm")
        axes[i].set_title(f'{feature} vs {target_variable}', fontsize=12)
        axes[i].set_xlabel(target_variable, fontsize=10)
        axes[i].set_ylabel(feature, fontsize=10)
        axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45, labelsize=8)
        axes[i].tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=8)

    # Offset for categorical features in the subplot grid
    offset = len(features)

    # Hide any unused axes
    for ax in axes[total_features:]:
        ax.axis('off')

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Based on the provided correlation information between features where the correlation is 0.7 or more, here are some observations for Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):

  • Strong Negative Correlations: Several pairs of features exhibit strong negative correlations, such as V2 and V14 with a correlation coefficient of -0.85353. This suggests that as the value of one feature increases, the value of the other decreases. Identifying such relationships is crucial for understanding the inverse dependencies between features.

  • Strong Positive Correlations: There are numerous instances of strong positive correlations, indicating that certain features move in the same direction. For example, V7 and V15 have a correlation of 0.86787, suggesting a strong direct relationship. Features with high positive correlations might convey redundant information.

  • Network of Correlated Features: Some features are correlated with multiple other features, forming a network of correlations. For example, V25 shows significant correlations with V27, V30, V32, and V33. This suggests that V25 might be a central feature in its domain, influencing or being influenced by various other features.

  • Potential for Dimensionality Reduction: The presence of strong correlations, both positive and negative, indicates opportunities for dimensionality reduction.

  • Implications for Model Training: High correlations between features can impact machine learning models. For linear models, multicollinearity can inflate the variance of the coefficient estimates, making them unstable. For tree-based models, highly correlated features can lead to preference for one feature over another, potentially affecting the model's performance.

  • Diverse Relationships: The varied nature of the correlations—spanning from very strong to moderate—across different feature pairs highlights the complex relationships in the dataset. It underscores the importance of a nuanced approach to feature selection and model building, considering both the strength and direction of these correlations.

Overall, the significant correlations between features underscore the need for careful data preprocessing, feature selection, and possibly dimensionality reduction to build effective and interpretable models.

Function to treat highly correlated features¶

In [104]:
# Identify highly correlated features in the dataframe and return a list of columns to remove.
def remove_highly_correlated_features(df, threshold=0.7):
    """
    Parameters:
    df (pd.DataFrame): The input dataframe.
    threshold (float): The correlation threshold to identify features as highly correlated.

    Returns:
    list: A list of columns that are highly correlated.
    """

    # Calculate the correlation matrix
    corr_matrix = df.corr().abs()

    # Select upper triangle of correlation matrix
    upper = corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape), k=1).astype(bool))

    # Find index of feature columns with correlation greater than threshold
    to_drop = [column for column in upper.columns if any(upper[column] > threshold)]

    return to_drop

Model evaluation criterion¶

The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures in a generator where there is no detection by model.
  • False positives (FP) are failure detections in a generator where there is no failure.

Which metric to optimize?

  • We need to choose the metric which will ensure that the maximum number of generator failures are predicted correctly by the model.
  • We would want Recall to be maximized as greater the Recall, the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives.
  • We want to minimize false negatives because if a model predicts that a machine will have no failure when there will be a failure, it will increase the maintenance cost.

# Builds multiple models, performs cross-validation, and returns models and their CV results.
def build_models_and_cross_validate(X_train, y_train, n_splits=5, random_state=1, scorer='recall'):
    """
    Parameters:
    - X_train: Features for the training set.
    - y_train: Target variable for the training set.
    - n_splits: Number of splits for cross-validation (default 5).
    - random_state: Random state for reproducibility (default 1).
    - scorer: Scoring metric for cross-validation (default 'recall').

    Returns:
    - models: List of tuples containing model names and model objects.
    - cv_results_df: DataFrame with model names and cross-validation results.
    - cv_mean_scores_df: DataFrame with model names and cross-validation mean scores.
    """
    # Define models
    models = [
        ("LR", LogisticRegression(random_state=random_state)),
        ("dtree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=random_state)),
        ("Bagging", BaggingClassifier(random_state=random_state)),
        ("RF", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=random_state)),
        ("GBM", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=random_state)),
        ("Xgboost", XGBClassifier(random_state=random_state, eval_metric="logloss"))
    ]

    cv_results = []
    model_names = []
    cv_mean_scores = []
    for name, model in models:
        kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=True, random_state=random_state)
        cv_result = cross_val_score(model, X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=scorer, cv=kfold)
        cv_results.append(cv_result)
        model_names.append(name)
        cv_mean_scores.append(cv_result.mean())

    cv_results_df = pd.DataFrame({'Model': model_names, 'CV_Results': cv_results})
    cv_mean_scores_df = pd.DataFrame({'Model': model_names, 'CV_Mean_Score': cv_mean_scores})
    return models, cv_results_df, cv_mean_scores_df

# Creates recall scores for each model.
def create_recall_scores(models, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, score_column_name='Recall'):
    """
    Parameters:
    - models: List of model objects.
    - X_train: Features for the training set.
    - y_train: Target variable for the training set.
    - X_val: Features for the validation set.
    - y_val: Target variable for the validation set.
    - score_column_name: Column name for the recall score (default 'Recall').

    Returns:
    - recall_scores_df: DataFrame with recall scores for each model.
    """
    recall_scores = []
    for name, model in models:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        recall_score_val = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
        recall_scores.append((name, recall_score_val))

    recall_scores_df = pd.DataFrame(recall_scores, columns=['Model', score_column_name])
    return recall_scores_df

# validation_recall_scores_df = create_recall_scores(models, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, 'Recall_Score_Validation')

# Function to tune a model using RandomizedSearchCV.
def tune_model(estimator, X_train, y_train, param_distributions, scoring, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, cv=5, random_state=1):
    """
    Parameters:
    - estimator: The model to be tuned.
    - X_train: Features for the training set.
    - y_train: Target variable for the training set.
    - param_distributions: Dictionary with parameters names as keys and distributions or lists of parameters to try.
    - scoring: Scoring metric for cross-validation.
    - n_iter: Number of parameter settings that are sampled.
    - n_jobs: Number of jobs to run in parallel.
    - cv: Number of cross-validation folds.
    - random_state: Random state for reproducibility.

    Returns:
    - best_params: Best parameters found by RandomizedSearchCV.
    - best_score: Best score obtained by RandomizedSearchCV.
    """
    randomized_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=estimator, param_distributions=param_distributions, scoring=scoring, n_iter=n_iter, n_jobs=n_jobs, cv=cv, random_state=random_state)
    randomized_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
    best_params = randomized_cv.best_params_
    best_score = randomized_cv.best_score_
    return best_params, best_score
In [111]:
# Builds and evaluates a model using the provided parameters and returns a DataFrame with recall scores.
def evaluate_tuned_model(model_name, classifier, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, best_params, datatype):
    """
    Parameters:
    - model_name: Name of the model (e.g., 'GBM_Tuned', 'LR_Tuned', 'Bagging_Tuned').
    - classifier: Classifier object (e.g., GradientBoostingClassifier, LogisticRegression).
    - X_train: Features for the training set.
    - y_train: Target variable for the training set.
    - X_val: Features for the validation set.
    - y_val: Target variable for the validation set.
    - best_params: Best parameters for the classifier from RandomizedSearchCV.
    - datatype: Type of data (e.g., '_org', '_over', '_un').

    Returns:
    - df_scores: DataFrame with model name and recall scores for training and validation sets.
    """
    # Build and fit the model using the best parameters
    model = classifier(**best_params, random_state=1)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Evaluate the model on the training and validation sets
    recall_train = recall_score(y_train, model.predict(X_train))
    recall_val = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))

    # Create a DataFrame with the results
    df_scores = pd.DataFrame({
        'Model': [model_name],
        f'Recall_Train_{datatype}': [recall_train],
        f'Recall_Val_{datatype}': [recall_val]
    })

    return df_scores
In [112]:
# Computes different metrics to check performance of a classification model.
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1

        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

# Plots the confusion_matrix with percentages
def confusion_matrix_plot(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

    • Undersampling (Un) also improves recall scores for most models, with particularly notable improvements for GBM and its tuned version (GBM_Tuned).

  4. Tuned Models:

    • GBM_Tuned shows improved recall scores compared to the original GBM model, especially on the oversampled and undersampled data.
    • LR_Tuned does not show significant improvement over the original LR model.
    • Bagging_Tuned shows a slight improvement over the original Bagging model on the undersampled data.

Final Model Selection¶

Based on the provided recall scores, the Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) tuned on undersampled data (gbm_tuned_un) appears to give the best performance without significant overfitting. Selection is further justified using following points:

  • High Recall Scores: GBM Tuned has high recall scores on both the training and validation sets for undersampled data (Recall_Train_Un = 0.90745, Recall_Val_Un = 0.88129), indicating strong performance in identifying the positive class.

  • Consistent Performance: The difference between the training and validation recall scores for GBM Tuned on undersampled data is relatively small (around 0.026), suggesting that the model is generalizing well and not overfitting significantly.

  • Improved Performance with Tuning: The tuned version of GBM (GBM_Tuned) shows improved performance compared to the original GBM model, especially on the undersampled data.

Define Pipeline¶

# Assuming best_params is a dictionary with the best hyperparameters
finalmodel_best_params = best_params_gbm_un

# Creating a new pipeline with best parameters
finalmodel_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("imputer", KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5)), # Impute missing values using KNNImputer
        ("undersampler", RandomUnderSampler(random_state=1)), # Use RandomUnderSampler for Under sampling the data
        ("gbm_tuned_un", GradientBoostingClassifier(
            **finalmodel_best_params,
            random_state=1,
        )), # Build Gradient Boosting Machine model using best parameters returned by RandomizedSearchCV
    ]
)

# Fit the model on training data
finalmodel_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

Renewable energy sources, notably wind energy, are crucial to our sustainable energy future. The ability to predict and prevent failures in wind turbine generators can significantly reduce operational and maintenance costs. Our analytical approach and machine learning models have identified key insights:

Important Features:

  • Top Predictive Features: Analysis reveals that V18, V36, and V3 are the most significant features influencing generator failure predictions. Close attention to these sensors could preempt costly downtimes.

  • Secondary Predictive Features: Features V13 and V12 also demonstrate moderate importance, suggesting that while they have a lesser impact, they still contribute valuable predictive power to the model.

Model Performance:

  • The Gradient Boosting Machine model tuned with undersampled data (gbm_tuned_un) emerged as the optimal model without overfitting, achieving an 91% recall on training data, an 88% recall on validation data, and an impressive 87% recall on unseen test data.

  • The model's robustness is further supported by 92% accuracy in identifying true negatives, essential for minimizing false alarm rates.

Other Important Insights:

  • Cost-Effective Maintenance: By accurately identifying true positive failure cases (TP), the model ensures repair efforts are timely and cost-effective, while minimizing the incidence of false negatives (FN) that could result in expensive generator replacements.

  • Maintenance Policy Recommendations: The insights gained from the model's feature importance can refine maintenance checks, focusing on high-impact factors and adjusting sensor data collection frequency to improve predictive accuracy.

  • Pipeline Deployment: The deployment of a machine learning pipeline incorporating the chosen GBM model will allow for real-time predictive analysis, further reducing maintenance response times and costs.

  • Future Enhancements: Continuous improvement of the machine learning model through the integration of additional data and advanced analytics will drive further cost savings and operational efficiency.

In conclusion, the predictive maintenance model not only fulfills the objective of reducing maintenance costs but also aligns with the broader goal of sustainable energy production by enhancing the reliability and efficiency of wind turbines. The company, ReneWind, is now equipped to implement a more proactive maintenance strategy, ensuring operational resilience and cost savings.

Other explanations:¶

  • KNNImputer Usage: Chosen for its ability to impute missing values by leveraging the underlying patterns in the data, KNNImputer uses the nearest neighbors approach, providing a nuanced estimation that simple mean or median replacement methods can't match.

  • imblearn.pipeline Usage: Utilized for its compatibility with resampling techniques, the imblearn.pipeline ensures that class balancing via methods like RandomUnderSampler is appropriately applied during the training process to prevent data leakage and maintain the integrity of cross-validation.
